    <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 mb-2 mt-4">Category theory connections</p>
    <ul>
      <li><a href="/reading/category-theory/milewski-07/">Milewski Ch.7</a> &mdash; isomorphisms in a category are invertible morphisms; Cayley's theorem is a special case of the Yoneda lemma</li>
      <li><a href="/reading/category-theory/milewski-01/">🍞 Milewski Ch.1</a> &mdash; isomorphisms as the fundamental notion of "sameness" in categories</li>
    </ul>
    </Neighbors>

    <!-- Translation notes -->
    <h3>Translation notes</h3>
    <p>Judson covers isomorphisms in Ch. 9 after cosets and normal subgroups. We bring it forward because the concept requires only bijective homomorphisms. Cayley's theorem appears in Ch. 5 of Judson. The connection to the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yoneda_lemma"><img src="/reading/wikipedia.svg" alt="wp" style="display:inline;height:1em;vertical-align:-0.1em;margin-right:0.2em;"/>Yoneda lemma</a> is not in Judson but is the categorical generalization: every object is determined by the morphisms into (or out of) it.</p>

    <PrevNext prev={{ href: "/reading/abstract-algebra/judson-03/", label: "Homomorphisms" }} next={{ href: "/reading/abstract-algebra/judson-05/", label: "Cosets and Lagrange's Theorem · 5 of 8" }} />

  </main>
